thout sin. Michnik employs deep historical analysis and keen political observation in his insightful five-point philosophical meditation on morality in public life, ingeniously expounding on history, religion, moral thought, and the present political climate in his native country and throughout Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDemocracyxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aJacobins. 0aPolitical ethics. 0aPost-communismzPoland. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh1 aCzarny, Roman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrudzinska Gross, Irena, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHunter, James Davison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarczyk, Agnieszka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatynia, Elzbieta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106725030 cprintz978030018597340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030020702640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300207026423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300207026/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY